<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-12-25T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-12-25T23:00:00-05:00" n="655" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d655">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3323: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-26T12:00:00+08:00">December 26,
                                1931—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 26—1:30
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1129. Following from American Consul General at Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“December 23, 5 p.m.</p>
                                <list>
                                    <label>1.</label>
                                    <item>Last evening Secretary Chao, who had just returned from
                                        visiting General Ma at Hailun, informed me that Ma had
                                        sufficient funds to support his troops for 3 months; that he
                                        was still acting under instructions of Nanking and that he
                                        would await the results of the visit of the League of
                                        Nations commission.</item>
                                    <label>2.</label>
                                    <item>No evidence to the effect that Ma has yielded to Japanese
                                        demands has been brought to the attention of this office,
                                        but judging by Chao’s remarks he is anxious in regard to
                                        expected operations of Japanese at Chinchow.[”]</item>
                                </list>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>